==English==
[[File:Death Actaeon BM VaseF176.jpg|right|thumb|[[Actaeon]], wielding a '''xiphos''', attacked by his own hounds; painted vase, circa 390-380 BCE]]
{{wikipedia}}
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|grc|ξίφος}}. {{doublet|en|seif}}.
===Noun===
{{en-noun|+|xiphoi|xiphe}}
# {{lb|en|historical}} A [[double-edged]], [[single-handed]] [[sword]], typically used by [[Ancient Greek]] [[hoplite]]s as a [[secondary]] [[weapon]] after the [[dory]] (thrusting [[spear]]) or [[javelin]].
====Usage notes====
* The plural ''xiphoi'' is modeled on analogy with similar Greek plurals in English, but would not be considered correct in Greek. The authentic Greek plural ''xiphe'' sees only occasional use in English.
